{
  "texts": [
    "That means the latency of a smaller DNN size (smaller input size) is lower than that of a bigger DNN size.",
    "To profile the latency of a DNN variant in the dynamic DNN for a particular batch size, we consider the worst-case execution latency which is when all the requests in the batch exit from the final exit branch.",
    "In addition, we assume that the accuracy characteristics of our 16 OFA-ResNet50-DETR variants are similar to that of YOLOv4 DNNs, meaning that the accuracy increases monotonically with the DNN input size.",
    "Note that, as benchmarked in (Sreedhar et al. 2022; Samplawski and Marlin 2021), the DETR model's backbone part is relatively more expensive in computation (60%-90% of the total execution time) than the transformer part (10%-40% of the total execution time) depending on the input size and batch size used.",
    "Hence, we do not consider a dynamic architecture for the transformer block in this work."
  ]
}